            <h2 id="corp-guide-heading" class="text-2xl sm:text-3xl font-extrabold text-white tracking-tight leading-snug">
              Choosing the Right Side-Hustle Business Structure
            </h2>
            <p class="mt-3 text-slate-400 text-sm leading-relaxed">
              Understanding <strong class="text-slate-200">when to switch from sole proprietor to LLC</strong> (or Limited Company) is one of the highest-ROI decisions a self-employed professional can make. The answer depends on your jurisdiction, your net profit level, and the cost of corporate compliance overhead.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div class="space-y-6 text-sm text-slate-400 leading-relaxed">
            <article>
              <h3 class="text-base font-bold text-slate-100 mb-2">The Self-Employment Tax Problem</h3>
              <p>
                Every dollar of profit from a sole proprietorship or sole trader business is subject to both <strong class="text-slate-300">income tax</strong> and <strong class="text-slate-300">self-employment / payroll taxes</strong>. In the US, this means 15.3% SE tax on top of ordinary income rates — effectively a penalty for entrepreneurship that W-2 employees don't pay in full. In the UK, Class 4 National Insurance adds 6% on profits between £12,570 and £50,270. These <strong class="text-slate-300">side hustle tax write offs</strong> are only partial — the SE tax deduction only offsets 50% of the SE tax burden.
              </p>
            </article>

            <article>
              <h3 class="text-base font-bold text-slate-100 mb-3">2026 Tax Landscape: Sole Trader vs. Corporate Structure Comparison</h3>
