          <div class="space-y-6 text-sm text-slate-400 leading-relaxed">
            <article>
              <h3 class="text-base font-bold text-slate-100 mb-2">The Debt Avalanche: Mathematical Optimum</h3>
              <p>
                The <strong class="text-slate-300">Debt Avalanche</strong> method prioritizes your highest-interest-rate debt first while paying minimums on all other balances. Every extra dollar you have beyond the minimum payment total gets directed at the debt costing you the most per month. This is the <strong class="text-slate-300">fastest way to pay off credit card debt</strong> in pure interest-saved terms — because the debt generating the most interest damage is eliminated first, reducing the compounding erosion on your net worth from day one.
              </p>
              <p class="mt-3">
                In a typical scenario with a $20,000 credit card at 22%, a $15,000 car loan at 7%, and a $10,000 personal loan at 14%, an avalanche approach with $500/month extra could save $3,000–$5,000 in total interest compared to Snowball over the same repayment period.
              </p>
            </article>

            <article>
              <h3 class="text-base font-bold text-slate-100 mb-2">The Debt Snowball: The Psychology of Momentum</h3>
              <p>
                The <strong class="text-slate-300">Debt Snowball</strong> method targets the smallest balance first, regardless of interest rate. When that smallest debt is cleared, the minimum payment that was going to it "rolls" into the next smallest debt — like a snowball gaining mass and momentum. Research by behavioral economists Dave Ramsey and others at Harvard Business School found that Snowball users were more likely to fully eliminate their debt than Avalanche users, because the quick wins reduce "debt fatigue" and reinforce the habit loop of consistent repayment.
              </p>
            </article>

            <article>
              <h3 class="text-base font-bold text-slate-100 mb-2">How to Accelerate Debt Payoff: The Universal Multiplier</h3>
              <p>
                Regardless of which method you choose, the single most powerful lever for <strong class="text-slate-300">how to accelerate debt payoff</strong> is your extra monthly payment budget — the amount you commit above all minimum payments. Even an additional $100/month can cut years off a debt repayment timeline. Our <strong class="text-slate-300">Debt Snowball vs Avalanche Planner</strong> above simulates both strategies simultaneously, showing you the exact month each individual debt is cleared, the total interest paid under each method, and the precise months shaved off your debt-free date.
              </p>
